\fs28 What is CPU History?
\fs32 \
\

\b0\fs24 If you want a graph of CPU usage in the Dock and nothing more, Activity Monitor is a lot of overhead for no good reason. CPU History is a solution.\
\
CPU History is a streamlined replacement for Apple's CPU Monitor (development stopped after 10.2, and no longer works on 10.5). 10.3 saw the replacement of CPU Monitor with Activity Monitor, but Activity Monitor uses lots of memory and CPU to update its list of running applications, network activity, and other system usage statistics.\
\
In timing tests, Activity Monitor (and its sister process, pmTool) used a combined 18-20% CPU on an iBook G4. CPU History 1.0 used 1.2-1.8% CPU to graph the same information. On a MacBook Pro, Activity Monitor and pmTool used a combined 2.9% CPU, while CPU History 1.1 used 0.1% CPU.\
\
CPU History 1.1 fully supports multicore machines, has a floating window for the graph, lets you customize update intervals (0.1s \'96 60s), graph colors, and bar widths, and graphs as small as single pixel differences in CPU usage.\
\
Activity Monitor, by comparison, has a floater, but only lets you customize update intervals (your choice of 0.5, 1, 2, or 5 seconds), set colors for the graph, and resolves to only two pixels in the graph.\
\
